Electron carriers are substances that can accept and give up electrons
as required. They often link oxidations and reductions in cells. The
main electron carrier in respiration is NAD (nicotinamide adenine
dinucleotide). In photosynthesis a phosphorylated version of NAD
is used, NADP (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate). The
structure of the NAD molecule is shown in gure 1.

This reaction demonstrates that reduction can be achieved by accepting
atoms of hydrogen, because they have an electron. Oxidation can
therefore be achieved by losing hydrogen atoms.
